objects.description:
SolarMarker is a malware family known for its info-stealing and backdoor capabilities, mainly delivered through search engine optimization manipulation to convince users to download malicious documents. Some of its capabilities include the exfiltration of auto-fill data, saved passwords, and saved credit card information from the victim’s web browsers. In addition to capabilities belonging to regular info-stealers, SolarMarker has additional capabilities such as file transfer and command execution received from a C2 server. One of the key techniques in which it invests effort is defense evasion, which consists of techniques like signed files, huge files, impersonation of legitimate software installations, and obfuscated PowerShell scripts.

This malware has been prevalent since September 2020 targeting US companies, and part of the infrastructure is still active as of 2022.
Recently, we've identified a new version of SolarMarker. In a recent blog post, we dived into the technical details of the newly identified activity, and specifically how this malware often changes and modifies its attack patterns,  for example - the recent version demonstrated an evolution from Windows Portable Executables (EXE files) to working with MSI files. According to the evidence we have, this campaign is still in development and we assess with medium confidence that it might go back to using executables files (EXE) as did in its earlier versions.
